<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The same sorts of remote control signals that can activate tracks on a CD player can activate tracks on an MP3 player soldered onto the cart PCB. The Japanese version of Bases Loaded has a sound chip that works much this way (see <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=762" class="postlink">previous topic</a>). But if you want to play expansion sound on a 72-pin system, you are going to need an add-on.<br /></div><br /><br />Too bad the ROM is missing the sample pack. Would be nice to check it out. I also read the topic about sdm's attempt and it's amazing. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> Too bad my polish sucks so I could communitcate with him about it. So the NES would force the player to buy an add on, however Famicom does not. Am I correct (just asking since I'm still not so sure) <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_lol.gif" alt=":lol:" title="Laughing" /> <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Because not all emulators have a compatible software license. More importantly, not all emulators run on sufficiently beefy hardware. For example, I could build a mapper for the NES containing an entire Game Boy chipset. It would run the ROM as a Game Boy ROM and forwards the video to the NES PPU. (In fact, Nintendo released a developer product called Wide Boy that did just that, and then turned it into a consumer product for Super NES called Super Game Boy.) Emulators that have trouble keeping up with the base system alone, such as PocketNES on GBA or SNEmulDS on Nintendo DS, would have a female dog of a time adding an 8080-family CPU and a Game Boy PPU to the mix.<br /></div><br /><br />Hm... you got a point there. Maybe it would be better focusing on the actual hardware...<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&