First of all, thanks for your comments.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I know how "play this MP3 file" could be made into a physical mapper: have the cart control a CD player. A CD player's remote control uses a serial protocol over a wired or infrared physical layer. So we just have to emulate a serial port, and the mapper turns this into commands to a (real or emulated) CD player.<br /><br />Or if you're willing to accept a 7 percent slowdown, you can use DPCM to play back a long sample within the ROM file. A long time ago, I made a <a href="http://pics.pineight.com/max-300.zip" class="postlink">demo</a> that plays "Max 300", a song from DDR, through a common mapper.<br /></div><br /><br />I see so you mean:<br /><br />NES CPU sends -&gt; CD Player, CD Playercheck=OK -&gt; Go directly to output. Yes, it's a good idea but I let's say that I don't want a damn addon, I just want it packed into my cartridge.<br /><br />Also why do refer your method with MP3 files? Wouldn't cda. files do the same job (for a CD addon)?<br /><br />Also I really dislike the method of using DPCM samples as well as 7 bit-PCM samples, since it's possible, shown by yourself and Memblers (found that few days ago) and the signal is distorted.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The short answer is yes.<br /><br />The FC runs audio through the cartridge (and the NES runs it through the expansion port iirc), so any external device can output any sound through the NES (this is how VRC6, N106, etc expansion sound works -- the hardware for that existed on the cartridge, not on the NES).  It's possible to have any amount of external hardware which runs outside of the NES that sort of "adds on" to the capabilities of the NES.<br /></div><br /><br />Yes, the Famicom used some pins (don't know which ones at the moment), which were used for those external soundchips and mappers. Did the FC internal audio device 2A03 run through those pins too?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Plus fabricating imaginary mappers (which that TMNT demo didn't do) is a big no-no.  It's hard enough to stay on top of mappers that actually exist.  Adding phoney ones to the mix doesn't do anyone any good.<br /><br />So the realistic answer is no.<br /></div><br /><br />If source codes were given by the developer(s), why not? <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />Btw. You're right. If this demo used a homebrew mapper, it wouldn't be functional on a emulator.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3763">Eightbit Allstar</a> — Fri Jan 02, 2009 9:09 pm</p><hr />
