<author><name><![CDATA[Disch]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-01-02T18:11:30-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-01-02T18:11:30-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4691&amp;p=41243#p41243</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4691&amp;p=41243#p41243"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Question: WAV - Mapper]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4691&amp;p=41243#p41243"><![CDATA[
The short answer is yes.<br /><br />The FC runs audio through the cartridge (and the NES runs it through the expansion port iirc), so any external device can output any sound through the NES (this is how VRC6, N106, etc expansion sound works -- the hardware for that existed on the cartridge, not on the NES).  It's possible to have any amount of external hardware which runs outside of the NES that sort of "adds on" to the capabilities of the NES.<br /><br />Probably the best way to visualize this concept is like the Sega CD and Sega 32X addons to Sega Genesis.  The idea is the same, only instead of having a seperate addon unit, all the parts would be included in every single cartridge.<br /><br />This, of course, is totally impractical.  And if you're going to go this far with NES addons you might as well not even bother with the NES part.<br /><br />Plus fabricating imaginary mappers (which that TMNT demo didn't do) is a big no-no.  It's hard enough to stay on top of mappers that actually exist.  Adding phoney ones to the mix doesn't do anyone any good.<br /><br />So the realistic answer is no.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=33">Disch</a> — Fri Jan 02, 2009 6:11 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
